Conclusions
Ultimately, I found that—in California during 2013, 2014, 2018, and 2021—air quality significantly associated with poverty rates. Specifically, for all four years, annual mean concentrations of PM2.5 (µg/m3) increased as the percent of people living below twice the federal poverty level increased (Figure 3). In other words, air quality was lower in census tracts with higher poverty rates.
